		<h4><div>Leo&#353; Jan&#225;&#269;ek&rsquo;s ‘manifesto on love’<br>&amp; pianist Jan Lisiecki</div></h4>
		<p>Our love affair continues! &ldquo;In the first half of this concert, we explore unrequited love again with Leo&#353; Jan&#225;&#269;ek&rsquo;s second string quartet,&rdquo; says Anne Manson. The composer nicknamed the work &lsquo;Intimate Letters&rsquo;, as it was inspired by his long and spiritual friendship with Kamila St&#246;sslov&#225;, a married woman 38 years his junior (Wikipedia).</p>
		<p>We like long and spiritual friendships, and we&rsquo;re nurturing a few of our own. In the second half, we welcome back our dearly-loved and awe-inspiring Jan Lisiecki, who opened last season with a four-star concert. </p>
		<p>The late Gwenda Nemerofsky, in her <i>Winnipeg Free Press</i> review, wrote of listening and picturing in her mind&rsquo;s eye more of a middle-aged piano virtuoso. &ldquo;Such confidence, attack, technical fluidity and enchanting sensitivity could only come from a decades-seasoned performer. Instead, the guest artist was a blond-haired, fresh-faced lanky young man.&rdquo;</p>
		<p><b>Love Hurts</b></p>
		<p>Leo&#353; Jan&#225;&#269;ek is one of Anne Manson&rsquo;s favourite composers, and two of the Czech&rsquo;s works will be performed this season. The connecting theme is unrequited love, with the <i>Kreutzer Sonata</i> on March 17th and <i>Intimate Letters</i> on this program.</p>
		<p>Jan&#225;&#269;ek&rsquo;s inspiration for the former piece was Leo Tolstoy&rsquo;s novella of the same name, but no such work of fiction was required for the second string quartet. That story was told in some 700 love letters.</p>
		<p>While affairs of the heart  may &ldquo;never help our worthwhile pursuits but only hinder them&rdquo; (Tolstoy), it&rsquo;s essential to the arts!</p>

